 
This document will attempt to explain the system of bins.  If you can think
of some command line type of operating system, that will help.  What we
are attempting to do here, is set up commands, individually.  In other words
each command is its own separate file.  This is very similar to that operating
system you have envisioned.  For example, the system will have different files
you run.  For example, in DOS:  Copy, Del, Move, etc. are a type of bins. 
In Unix: Cp, Mkdir, Rmdir, etc. are types of bins. 
 
What we are creating is a command path, which is a directory of commands that
a player can use, and then each command is its own file.  On Darkwind, you
could find the bins for all the emotions in /cmds/soul.  There each file has
a '_' prepended to it.  So, the smile command will be _smile.c  Any bins you
code will have the same syntax.
 
To add the command path to the player, in your guild object, add the following
code:  (Assuming this is for a guild.)
 
#include <daemons.h>
#define GCMDS "/cmds/guilds/my_special_guild"
 
  CMD_D->add_path(GCMDS, this_player());
  CMD_D->rehash(GCMDS);
 
Next, in the actual bin file, its code would look something like this:
 
int do_command(string sArg) {
  if(!sArg) {
    write("do what to who?\n");
    return 1;
  }
  Do your command code here.
  return 1;
}
 
The 'do_command' will always be the name of the core function.  The filename 
will always be what you want the player to type to execute that command.
However, you can specify other things to type for that command:
  
string *command_aliases() { return ( ({"protct","prtect"}) ); }
 
In place of the protct or prtect (for protect) you can do others.  Note, that
you don't have to alias the filename (_protect.c in this case.)
 
As far as any other specifics, there aren't any.  Bins should go in the /cmds
dir and you'll need to get a Demi to create that dir, and give you access to
it.  The command code should be like the code to any other LPC function.
